<FONT COLOR="#004400">
<CENTER><H2>Robert Lowell (1917-77)</H2>
</CENTER>
</FONT>

<PRE>
<FONT SIZE=3>
	      Father's Bedroom

	In my Father's bedroom:
	blue threads as thin
	as pen-writing on the bedspread,
	blue dots on the curtains,
	a blue kimono,
	Chinese sandals with blue plush straps.
	The broad-planked floor
	had a sandpapered neatness.
	The clear glass bed-lamp
	with a white doily shade
	was still raised a few
	inches by resting on volume two
	of Lafcadio Hearn's
	<I>Glimpses of unfamiliar Japan</I>.
	Its warped olive cover
	was punished like a rhinoceros hide.
	In the flyleaf:
	'Robbie from Mother.'
	Years later in the same hand:
	'This book has had hard usage
	On the Yangtze River, China.
	It was left under an open
	porthole in a storm.'
</FONT>
	[(from <I>Life Studies</I>) <I>Selected Poems</I>]
	Copyright (c) 1965 Faber and Faber
</PRE>

<H3>Biographical Notes
</H3>
<FONT SIZE=3><UL>
<LI>Born: Mar.  1, 1917, Boston
<LI>Died: Sept.  12, 1977 (from a heart attack)
<LI>Full Name: Robert Traill Spence Lowell, Jr.
<LI>Married: Jean Stafford (fiction-writer, divorced in 1948); Elizabeth Hardwick (writer).
<LI>Education: Harvard University, Kenyon College (undergraduate degree in classics)
<LI>Influenced by: Elizabeth Drew's <I>Discovering Poetry</I> (1933)
<LI>Roman Catholicism: An interest in it "dominates his earlier volumes <I>Land of Unlikeness</I> (1944), <I>Lord Weary's Castle</I> (1946), and <I>The Mills of the Kavanaughs</I> (1951)." (Jerome Mazzaro) Converted to Catholicism (1940).
<LI>Awards: Pulitzer Prize with <I>Lord Weary's Castle</I> (1946); Pulitzer Prize with <I>The Dolphin</I> 
(1973).
<LI>Works: <I>Land of Unlikeness</I> (1944), <I>Lord Weary's Castle</I> (1946), <I>The Mills of the Kavanaughs</I> (1951), <I>Life Studies</I> (1959), <I>The Old Glory</I> (1965) [a trilogy of plays], <I>For the Union Dead</I> (1964), <I>Near the Ocean</I> (1967), <I>Notebook 1967-68</I> (1969) [later extended into <I>History</I>, <I>For Lizzie and Harriet</I> and <I>The Dolphin</I> (1973)], and <I>Day by Day</I> (1977).
</UL>
</FONT>

